deck_description:
Prank-Kids

https://youtu.be/TgiNydtVXOQ

All Main Deck "Prank-Kids" monsters have effects that trigger if they are sent to the GY as Fusion or Link Materials for the Summon of a "Prank-Kids" monster, and afterwards, allow you to Special Summon from the hand or Deck a "Prank-Kids" monster with a different name than the one whose effect was activated. Their Fusion and Link Monsters each have one monster with 3000 ATK and two monsters with 2000 ATK. The ones with 3000 ATK are a Level 10 Fusion Monster and a Link-4 Link Monster, whose effects includes Tributing themselves to destroy all monsters ("Prank-Kids Battle Butler") or all Spells/Traps ("Prank-Kids Rip-Roarin-Roaster") your opponent controls. Meanwhile, those with 2000 ATK (Level 5 for Fusion Monsters and Link-2 for Link Monsters) have various effects that are usually related to battle. All Extra Deck "Prank-Kids" monsters also have effects that recover another card(s) from the GY, either by being destroyed by the opponent's card while in your possession (those with 3000 ATK) or by Tributing themselves (the ones with 2000 ATK). The Fusion Monsters have abilities to Special Summon a monster(s) from the GY, while the Link Monsters add a card(s) to your hand from the GY instead.

Gaia The Fierce Knight

 

  "Gaia The Fierce Knight", known as "Gaia the Dark Knight"Â  (Ankoku Kishi Gaia) in Japan, is an archetype of Level 7 Warrior monsters that includes "Gaia The Fierce Knight" and monsters based on it who all have 2300 ATK and 2100 DEF. All of its members are DARK and EARTH monsters, except for the LIGHT "Charging Gaia the Fierce Knight". This archetype is related to the "Black Luster Soldier" archetype. The "Gaia Knight" series is a subset of this archetype, although it is excluded from support.

deck_excerpt: Spell, Trap, Monster Effect, you name it, just negate, negate and negate. If you don't open rituals, you can still do the usual Trickstar shenanigans
deck_description: I like it when I can play yugioh, I also like it when my opponent can't play yugioh... Well in a way that doesn't seem too unfair... Not FTK or pseudo FTK anyway. As I read it, the Herald cards can basically negate anything and are not once per turn, but they require fairies to work and low level Herald monsters themselves aren't great, then it came across me that trickstars are decent and they are all light fairies, then I combined the 2 and made this deck, they work surprisingly well together so I thought I should share it. So Herald of Perfection is our main boss monsters here, our main goal is to negate anything the opponent do and out resource them with advantage generating Trickstars. With a hand of 6 fairies, you can certainly do that. Spell, Trap, Monster Effect, you name it, just negate, negate and negate. The basic combo is as follows: 1, you need Herald of Perfection, Dawn of the Herald (Ritual Spell), and Cyber Angel Benten or alternatively Pre-prep and prep of rituals as they searches the three mentioned above. Extra-foolish will search any one of the three. 2, if you have all 3, use Cyber Angel Benten as tribute to ritual summon Herald in defense position(Unless you have honest). Now active Cyber Angel Benten's search as CL-1, Ritual Spell's effect as CL-2, this will chain block your opponent from Ashing your search effect However they can still ghost belle you just keep in mind.Â Cyber Angel Benten's effect allows you to search any light fairy type monster, which is basically entire deck. Now ritual spell allows you to addÂ Â Cyber Angel Benten back to your hand, you now have Herald on field and one search. 3, Search targets are usually Trickstar Candina(Your trickstar engine starter if you don't already have one) Honest(To protect Herald from battle), Eva (Provide more fairies for latter use), Trickstar Lilybell(For GY recovery)   If you don't have the 3 combo pieces, chances are you have a lot of Trickstar cards, then you can do the usual Trickstar shenanigans, like droll-reincarnation combo. I don't cover it here since you can find those in many other places.   Some key cards explained: Herald of Perfection: Note this card can only negate activation of cards, not effects, so be sure to negate continuous s/t when they first activates or you can't destroy them later on. Honest: only run two as you don't really want to see more than one in your hand, two is a great number, help protect herald and run over big beaters. Barrier statue of Heavens: Side deck tech option, if you facing some danger dark warrior stuff, just search this using Cyber Angel and summon it, they can't really do anything if you also have an honest in hand to protect it. Eva: You don't want to discard this card first, use some ritual monsters first and then discard this, it allows you to go +2 by adding lilybell and orange light to your hand. Extra-Foolish burial: dump Herald of Arch light and you can search any of the missing ritual stuff, dump N'tss you can pop a floodgate or problematic monster. Don't use it if you can't get 3 combo pieces complete or want to use the droll-reincarnation combo as you can't set cards after you used it. Scapegoat: Sadlly at 1 now so when you have it, good make borrelsword and skill them, if you don't, don't be sad. Pot of Extravagance: You don't go into extra deck very often, so more card advantage is always good. 3 pre-prep: It's a +1, what more do you want? 3 prep: Do not use it to add back ritual spell though, you use it to search both ritual monsters, you only want to summon herald once so getting ritual spell back is often meaningless. Herald of Orange light: You go -1 but it's important to have, basically a veiler + orge, prevent your opponent from setting up an unbreakable board or summoning a crazy strong boss monster. The other two small Heralds are too situational. Note this card can snipe hand trap as well if you are desperate. Some cards I didn't run explained: Impcantation monsters: they bricks more often than I expected as we only run 1 summonable Ritual monster here, running multiple Impcantations would brick more often than help. Also when they hit the field, you can't really get them off the field as you can't link them off, thus hindering the use of Trickstar Lycoris and Lillybell. Hand traps: I side them because if you can get Herald out, you don't really need hand traps as every fairy in your hand become a handtrap whatsoever. The only hand trap I run is Herald of orange light, it's basically an effect veiler + Ghost orge in one. It's also a fairy, so you can use it with Herald of perfection and search it with Eva's effect(Don't search it using Cyber Angel though). However if you go second, swap some ritual stuff for hand traps and going second cards in case your opponent make an unbreakable board. Herald of Ultimateness:Â  Level 12 require a lot more resources, the ritual spell doesn't give you resource, it only have 200 more atk and def, can only negate ss, really not worth it for its cost. Pot of desires: Already running pot of extravagance, don't really want to banish Eva or some of the Trickstars though, as we are not running 3 of everything. Extra deck on the other hand we don't often go into. Ritual Sanctuary: It's a -1, the field spell itself doesn't do anything and you always prefer light stage, you don't really need this as you have pre-prep which is a +1, card advantage here is important as you are trading resource 1 for 1 with your opponent.

Kalin Kessler

Kalin was once the leader of The Enforcers (Team Satisfaction in the original version), which consisted of himself, Yusei Fudo, Crow Hogan and Jack Atlas. He met with the trio for the first time when he approached them with the idea for the Team. He fought for his own ideals and unique sense of unity and gave his team a true glimpse of hope under the despairing circumstances of the Satellite. The team managed to conquer all the team areas in the Satellite by beating the other Duel Gangs. During the face-off with the final gang, one of them almost killed Yusei by pushing him off the roof, but Kalin saved him. After conquering all the zones in Satellite, Kalin got into a fight with a kid from Team Insect, something that prompted Crow and Jack to go against Kalin and leave the team. Later, when Sector Security began arresting Duelists in Satellite, Kalin decided to take action into his own hands and blew up a part of the Security.

Burning Abyss

https://youtu.be/uNmYlnj9BF8

So far, all Main Deck "Burning Abyss" monsters, with the exception of the Level 6 Ritual Monster "Malacoda", are Level 3 DARK Fiend monsters, and share three effects: they are destroyed if the player controls a monster other than a "Burning Abyss" monster, can be Special Summoned from the hand if the player controls no Spell/Trap Cards, and have a unique effect that is activated when it is sent to the Graveyard (except "Rubic, Malebranche of the Burning Abyss", which instead is a Tuner monster[1]). Use "Tour Guide From the Underworld" to search out any "Burning Abyss" monster or use "Crane Crane" to Summon them from the Graveyard. Their effects will be negated so they won't be destroyed by their own effect. This ensures that you can overlay into Rank 3 monsters like "Dante". The archetype's swarming abilities make it a potent Rank 3 Xyz Deck. They can perform Rank 3 Xyz Summons quickly while maintaining the player's hand advantage.
Alich Alichino Alichino, the "Harlequin" Negates the effects of a targeted face-up monster on the field until the end of the turn.
Barbar Barbariccia Barbariccia, the "Curly Beard" Banishes up to 3 targeted "Burning Abyss" cards in the controller's Graveyard, except "Barbar", then inflicts 300 damage to the opponent for each banished card.
Cagna Harrowhound Cagnazzo, the "Nasty Dog" Sends a "Burning Abyss" Spell/Trap Card from the controller's Deck to the Graveyard.
Calcab Hacklespur Calcabrina, the "Grace Stomper" Returns a targeted Set Spell/Trap Card on the field to the hand.
Cir Guttlehog Ciriatto, the "Wild Hog" Special Summons a targeted "Burning Abyss" monster in the controller's Graveyard, except "Cir".
Draghig Dragonel Draghignazzo, the "Big Nasty Dragon" The controller chooses and places a "Burning Abyss" card from their Deck on top of the Deck.
Farfa Farfarel Farfarello, the "Goblin" Banishes a targeted monster on the field until the End Phase.
Graff Grabbersnitch Graffiacane, the "Dog-Scratcher" Special Summons a "Burning Abyss" monster from the controller's Deck, except "Graff".
Libic Libbiocco Libicocco, the "Libyan Hothead" The controller Special Summons 1 Level 3 DARK Fiend monster from their hand with its effects negated.
Malacoda Hellraker Malacoda, the "Evil Tail" Sends 1 "Burning Abyss" monster from your hand to the Graveyard to decrease the ATK and DEF of an opponent's monster by that sent monster's. If sent from the field to the Graveyard, sends 1 card on the field to the Graveyard.
Rubic Rubicant Rubicante, the "Red-Faced Terror" Tuner monster
Scarm Scaramallion Scarmiglione, the "Troublemaker" The controller adds a Level 3 DARK Fiend monster from their Deck to their hand during the End Phase of the turn "Scarm" was sent to the Graveyard.

deck_excerpt: The third most current version of my Dark Magician deck. After the failure of trying to integrate Lair of Darkness cards, I decided to keep it straigh
deck_description: The third most current version of my Dark Magician deck. After the failure of trying to integrate Lair of Darkness cards, I decided to keep it straight DM and add a little more draw power to the deck itself.  The Eye of Timaeus is a good card and all, but it is a brick that has a lot of potential. So I replaced it with the Keeper of Dragon Magic to build up the number of monsters in this deck that can be normal summoned. Keeper of Dragon Magic and Polymerization can be swapped with the Eye of Timaeus to lower card count and be more direct.  I feel like Torrential Tribute can really do good with Eternal Soul protecting DM. But I don't like the fact that I can still risk losing my cards. So I added 2x Drowning Mirror Force and 2x Mirror Force to the extra deck to be flexible in the event that torrential tribute is not helping. Battle Fader and Scapegoat are the Plan C for this to get a mini-wall out there for linking.  Dark Illusion is a great card IMO that protects almost all your monsters and can even work on your opponent's monsters to stop an effect. I feel it is a hidden gem that isn't known yet for DM. Dark Horizon is in the same boat but is hesitant if it wants to stay or not. It is very good for special summoning any of the Dark Spellcasters, depending on how screwed you are but you have to take the damage in order to use it. Dark Horizon could be very useful for getting out Apprentice Illusion Magician and get DM to your hand or even getting the DM out instead. Dark Illusion and Dark Horizon were meant to be swapped out with each other but could be together for the best coverage.  2x Eternal Souls. I find that 3x is too risky to run and that I will brick more often.  1x Dark Magic Attack for that quick removal of the back row.  Cosmo Brain is the card that I get questioned on. I like that it can become stronger than DM by discarding DM to the GY by 400 ATK and be able to still bring out the DM from hand or deck. Another hidden gem that is well known.  Mana Dragon Zirnitron, another situation like Dark Horizon, is a great card that can bring back Eternal Soul and start up DM domination. The problem I have is it is a possible brick. You have to hope your opponent will make your spell/trap card leave the field to become viable. Possible Side Deck but is up to the player.  Upstart Golbin and the Spellbooks for that draw power. I was thinking of running Wind Witches but feel that Wind Witches could be separatedÂ from DM since how good it is by itself.

deck_excerpt: - Can both aggro and control the game - Elemental HERO Shining Flare Wingman - As consistent as superheroes get
deck_description: Rating: 6/10 Uh, Treetop, this is pretty much the same Hero deck as last metagame. Yes. I know. It's great. Have you seen it? It's also been slightly more optimized since then. This deck can easily summonÂ Elemental HERO Shining Flare Wingman. It can also pretty much any other HERO Fusion if you play the fusion requirements, but I went for a more consistent build. You can easily throwÂ Elemental HERO Plasma ViceÂ into this particular build because of Sparkman. Strengths: - Tonnes of backrow, largely all chainable - Extremely consistent - Mad resource loops through Stratos, Vyon, Mist, Pot of Avarice - Power plays through miracle fusion - Summon the sickest HERO fusions - Very aggro Weakness: - Fights slowly through negation - Losing your only playstarter makes it a tough game to win - Shinging Flare Wingman etc requires some bricks - Called by the Grave on shadow mist hurts a lot (It's also being played a lot more in the current metagame) Trinities: - 2nd Copy ofÂ Elemental HERO Shadow Mist - 2nd Copy ofÂ Reinforcement of the Army - 3rdÂ Copy ofÂ Reinforcement of the Army -Â Elemental HERO Honest NeosÂ (Semi-Forbidden) Interactions of note: -Â Miracle FusionÂ onÂ Versago the DestroyerÂ andÂ Elemental HERO Sparkman -Â Vision HERO VyonÂ sendsÂ Elemental HERO Shadow MistÂ to search for any HERO andÂ Polymerization, which makes any Attribute HERO Fusion. -Â Mask ChangeÂ orÂ Form ChangeÂ onÂ Elemental HERO Absolute ZeroÂ intoÂ Masked HERO Acid -Â Tour Guide from the UnderworldÂ searchesÂ Versago the Destroyer -Â Armageddon Knight,Â Future Fusion,Â Lavalval Chain, orÂ Foolish BurialÂ sendingÂ Shaddoll DragonÂ (Instead of the usual Shadow Mist) -Â Elemental HERO StratosÂ plus revival is 6800 damage throughÂ Elemental HERO Honest Neos. Any 1200+ATK HERO in hand is a 2 card OTK. -Â Elemental HERO Absolute ZeroÂ gains its effect even when sent to the GY as Link material.

I know how much you guys really like my Trickstar deck profiles since they get so many views so I decided to make another one for 2019! The new Trickstar monster, Trickstar Corobane is a searchable Honest for Trickstars that boosts the decks potential even more than before. The new Pot of Extravagance also helps push this decks limits even further since Trickstars don't really use their extra deck for the most part except with Scapegoat and now that Scapegoat is at 1 because of the banlist, it isn't a really great card anymore being a 1 of. I know you guys may be thinking why two Extravagance and two Pot of Desires? Well it's because when playtesting I didn't see both a Desires and an Extravagance in most of my opening hands. If you don't like Desires you could switch it out to two Pot of Duality, but I like two Desires and two Extravagance. This deck definitely wants to go first every time possible. Having three Gozen Match and all the Solemns really hurts your opponent and lets you otk fast turn three when you go first. Plus the Trickstar Reincarnation and Droll & Lock Bird combo is still viable so going first three Reincarnation and three Droll is a must in the main deck. Overall this deck is really solid and hardly ever bricks, at least from my experience whenever I was making it from scratch and testing it. A lot of the side deck I dedicated to Thunder Dragons since it is a huge threat to Trickstars. The reason for Super Polymerization in the side deck is to bring out Predaplant Dragostapelia using your opponents Thunder Dragon monsters going second since Dragostapelia requires a fusion monster (Colossus or Titan) plus another dark monster (any Thunder Dragon monster) and they cannot respond to it because Super Poly says they cannot respond to the cards effect. I really hope you all enjoy the deck and stick around for more!

Geargia

 

Playing Style

All 8 "Geargia" monsters focus heavily on searching out each other, swarming the field in the process and Summoning Rank 3 and 4 Xyz Monsters, especially their ace cards, "Geargiagear Gigant XG" and "Gear Gigant X". Each monster has a different effect to search out cards: "Geargiano" Special Summons any Level 4 Machine monster from the Graveyard by Tributing itself, meaning that the card can be good to support other archetypes; "Geargiano Mk-II" can do the same as "Geargiano", but only with "Geargia" monsters, however it can also Special Summon the monster from the hand; "Geargiano Mk-III" do the same as "Geargiano Mk-II", but only if it is Special Summoned by the effect of a "Geargia" card; "Geargiarmor" search any "Geargia" from the Deck each time it is flipped face-up and is a solid wall with 1900 DEF; "Geargiaccelerator" helps to swarm the field, as it can Special Summon itself from your hand and has the bonus effect of adding another Geargia from your Graveyard to your hand when it goes to the Graveyard; "Geargiarsenal" can Tribute itself to Special Summon any "Geargia" from your Deck and also gains 200 ATK for each "Geargia" you control, even itself; "Geargiattacker" destroys Spell/Trap Cards on the field, up to the number of "Geargia" monsters you control each time it is flipped face-up.

World Chalice

https://youtu.be/L19tL7rwLSA

Playing Style

Being one of the first archetypes to focus on Link Summoning, the "World Chalice" archetype explores the intricacies of the newly-introduced mechanic. To that end, the archetype focuses on initiating multiple Link Summons in quick succession, all while promoting combos that extend the longevity of this style of play, namely through helping the controller amass more monsters in the hand or on the field to use as Link Materials. The archetype also encourages the controller carefully consider the placement of cards on their field, particularly by emphasizing the linking of Link Monsters with other monsters in order to gain boons via their effects.

The archetype's main strategy is the rapid amassing of Link Materials on the field to Link Summon Link Monsters, mainly by using Normal Monsters as a medium. To that end, several of its Main Deck monsters are Normal Monsters, namely "Beckoned by the World Chalice", "Chosen by the World Chalice", and "Crowned by the World Chalice", all of which possess different Levels, Attributes, and Types, and either 0 ATK or DEF. The archetype's Main Deck Effect Monsters are designed to further this strategy. The first effect of "World Chalice Guardragon" allows the controller to send it from the hand or field to the GY in order to negate the activation of a card that targets a linked monster and destroy it, thus offering protection to the controller from threats to the archetypes' Link Monsters. This also places "Guardragon" in the GY to enable its second effect, banishing it from the GY to Special Summon a Normal Monster from the GY to one of the controller's zones that a Link Monster points to. "Lee the World Chalice Fairy" enables the controller to add a "World Chalice" monster from their Deck to their hand if Normal or Special Summoned, assisting the player in providing monsters to Special Summon with the common effect of the archetype's Link Monsters. "Lee" also allows the controller to recover it from the GY to their hand if they send a monster from their hand or field to the GY. Both monsters have great synergy with each other as a result, given that the latter can place monsters in the GY in the process of recurring itself, which the former can then Special Summon for the controller to continue their combos.

Pierre the Gambler

Pierre the Gambler, known in Japan as Mitsuo ( Mitsuo) is Alexis Rhodes' childhood classmate and a world famous gambler, having mastered games from blackjack to poker. In primary school, Pierre would play games of chance with other students, always having them bet their prized possessions. After losing a game of Duel Monsters to Alexis, he steals her red hankerchief, which had been bet on the Duel. Years later, he arrives at Duel Academy where he asks Chancellor Sheppard and Vellian Crowler to let him duel Alexis. When they turned him down, he ended up taking out the Duel Academy security team that Chancellor Sheppard summoned until Alexis arrives agreeing to the duel. He finally duels with Alexis, but loses. In the end, it is revealed he actually has a crush on Alexis and returns the handkerchief to her. However, Alexis does not return these feelings and Pierre then leaves with Jaden Yuki trying to bid him farewell in the right way.

Also try to take advantage of the combo between Soul and Cursed, activating Soul to make use of it before adding it back to your hand to prevent destruction, and then immediately being able to attack directly to seal the effect. deck_name: Reversal Quiz FTK - Danger! Dark World Deck
deck_excerpt: An FTK deck using Reversal Quiz and Danger! cards
deck_description:
Deck Created By: Big Crunch (Deck Inspiration: Slash Draw FTK) Main Goal: To gather the 4 main cards that will accomplish the FTK and to thin out the deck until it only contains monster cards or one spell card (unless the combo stops). How to Accomplish: Use the monsters to swarm the field and also use the draw spell cards to thin the deck and add cards to hand. (Info Below) Monsters
  • Danger! Cards - Use to swarm the field (Especially with Dogman and Nessie) and thin out the deck.Â (Some monster can be Normal summoned if necessary)
  • Dr. Frankenderp - If Emergency Teleport is on hand, use the card and summon this card then activate the effect to draw a card. If not, Normal Summon or Special Summon using Saryuja. (You can only use the effect once)
  • Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite - Use it to return an important monster card or Temple of the Kings (Free Monster) if its on the graveyard. (You can only use the effect to Special Summon once) (Extra monster to Normal Summon if necessary)
  • Blackwing - Steam the Cloak - Use it to summon tokens (Saryuja can help) and to help a bit on swarming. (You can tribute a card to Special Summon it from the Graveyard) (You can only Special Summon it once)Â (Extra monster to Normal Summon if necessary)
  • Broww, Huntsman of Dark World - If discarded, a card is added (Extra monster to Normal Summon if necessary)
  • Shaddoll Beast - If discarded, a card is added (Only once though)
Draw Spells
  • Upstart Goblin - Hand neutral card (Helps with thinning)
  • Allure of Darkness - Hand neutral card (Helps with thinning and removing unecessary Dark cards)
  • Card Destruction - Card that replaces your entire hand with new cards (DON'T SEND THE 4 MAIN CARDS TO THE GRAVEYARD EVER!!!) (Use it if hand is bad, hand is filled with discard cards or when hand is filled with many cards) (Helps with thinning a lot if in a right moment)
  • The Beginning of the End - A +2 card when Graveyard is filled with Dark monsters (7+ Dark cards to be precise) (Helps with thinning and drawing) (Avoid using two at the same time unless the Graveyard is filled)
  • Into the Void - A situational Upstart Goblin (When you have 3+ cards in your hand, you can use it)
Other Card
  • Emergency Teleport - Use it on Frankenderp (If Frankenderp is already used, use it as a discard)
  After that, you can go to these Extra Deck cards
  • Â Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack - Basically, a mini Galaxy Tomahawk. Use it to swarm the field with tokens. (A mini Swarmer)
  • Saryuja Skull Dread - Use it to refill your hand with new cards and get rid unecessary ones. (Summon it using 4 monsters [most of the time] unless its really necessary)
  • Akashic Magician - Use it to return an important monster (Mostly Saryuja)
  • Wee Witch's Apprentice - A two arrowed Link monster that is good for having two Extra Deck monsters (Also a Dark monster)
  • Space Insulator - A Link monster that can use any monster for summon (Good when tokens are out) (Also a Dark monster)
  • LANphorhynchus - A Link monster that can use any monster for summon and also good for having two Extra Deck monsters (A good card?)
  • Link Spider - Good for token renaming (For Saryuja)
  Then, here are the card you need on the field at all times   Main Cards
  • Â Reversal Quiz - if the setup is done, use this card to swap with your opponents life points
  • Temple of the Kings - use it to immediately activate the trap card
  • Wall of Revealing Light - use it to lower you life points as much as possible (but not 0)
  • Fuhma Shuriken - Set this on the field and after the setup is done, this will finish of the opponent (almost all of the time)
  The consistency of the can be improved, so you can adjust the deck as much as you want.

deck_excerpt: Spyral Warrior Extra Link Aqua Dolphin Turbo (Going First) (Post December 2019 Banlist)
deck_description: In my Pure Trickstar build for 2019 I asked you guys if you wanted a custom Spyral deck or something else, and it seems that you guys wanted the custom Spyral deck as the deck got both three likes AND a comment which is amazing! Thank you so much for telling me what deck content you guys want and for supporting me. Now I've been fooling around with the Warrior engine a little bit combined with Spyrals. These two go together very nicely since SPYRAL Super Agent is a Warrior type monster as well as SPYRAL Tough even though I decided to only put one Tough in the deck. You always want to go first with this deck if possible. A Warrior monster plus a Warrior extender or a Super Agent in your opening hand means you will be able to extra link your opponent if you are going first. Also the deck is crazy because I've made it so you can loop Neo-Spacian Aqua Dolphin's effect multiple times going first to take handtraps and monsters in general out of your opponent's hand so they can't play their next turn and will have to scoop. The way this works is once you summon Dolphin the first time and use it's effect, you can then use it for link material for Isolde and then bring it back outÂ from the graveyard or banished pile with other extenders such as the equip spell, D.D.R, or Monster Reborn, etc... You can also use Isolde's effect to send four equip spells from your deck to grave in order to special summon Neo Space Connector which will allow you to use it's effect to send itself and special summon Dolphin from grave to use his effect again. The other combo to loop Dolphin's effect is using Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade in the graveyard to banish Dolphin and another Warrior monster and then use D.D.R to send the Divine Sword you just added to special summon Dolphin again. Then proceed to use Divine Sword again and banish two Warrior monsters and use Dolphin's effect to pitch Divine Sword to take another monster out of your opponent's hand. Another way to pull off this Divine Sword Dolphin combo is using Destrudo The Lost Dragon's Frisson to synchro into Power Tool Dragon and use its effect to force your opponent to choose the D.D.R from your deck, and add it to your hand. Then loop the Divine Sword and D.D.R and Dolphin. I've been able to win games on ygopro with just Dolphin's effect going first because I loop Dolphin four or five times and then they can't play because they don't have the monsters they need to go off into their combos in their hand anymore. The deck can brick sometimes, but I believe I have made it the as consistent as it can possibly be made. The brick ratio I would say isn't too high but sometimes it can happen. I will now explain how to extra link your opponent. Firstly, you need to summon two Warrior monsters and go into Isolde, Two Tales of The Noble Knights. Then use her effect to send four equip spells from deck to grave to special summon a Super Agent or Tough from deck, then you should be able to go into Summon Sorceress with Isolde and another Warrior monster besides Super Agent and use her effect to special summon another Super Agent or Tough and then use those two monsters to go into SPYRAL Double Helix. Then you can use Double Helix to special summon SPYRAL Master Plan and use her effect to add SPYRAL MISSION -Â  Rescue from your deck to hand. You can also use Dolphin's effect to send Rescue to grave as cost and use Rescue later. The next step is to go into Knightmare Unicorn using Summon Sorc, Double Helix and Master Plan. If you don't already have SPYRAL Resort on the field then go ahead and set a spell/trap you don't need from your hand facedown before you summon Unicorn, and use Master Plan's effect and Unicorn's effect to send Rescue to grave to shuffle that card you set back into the deck, or if you do have Resort on the field already then shuffle Resort back into the deck instead of a facedown spell/trap in your hand you don't need. Then use Rescue in grave to banish itself to special summon Master Plan back to use her effect to add another Rescue and go into Knightmare Mermaid using Unicorn and use it's effect to send that Rescue from hand to grave and special summon Knightmare Corruptor Iblee from the deck. And now you can link into Knightmare Cerberus using Master Plan and Iblee right under Mermaid. The idea is just to keep looping Rescue and the SPYRAL MISSION - Assault in the deck to keep special summoning Master Plan and/or other Spyral monsters from grave and use SPYRAL Quik-Fix to get SPYRAL GEAR - Big Red to loop Master Plan an addition time. At the end of all that special summon looping, end with Quik-Fix and use it to make Linkuriboh in the other link zone, completing the extra link. It will be impossible for your opponent to get over this unless they main Evenly Matched or Ra Sphere Mode which is unlikely. Games two and three its best to make Trigate Wizard and co-link it times three so you can negate their Evenly Matched if they try to use it on you during their following turn after you go first. You can even use Summon Sorc to special summon Quik-Fix from the deck after summoning Power Tool Dragon since Power Tool is a Machine type monster and so is Quik-Fix. I did consider going second as an option if you don't win the rps or dice roll while building this deck from scratch of course! That's why I added Crusadia Arboria to the deck as an extender, because not only is it a Warrior type monster and a free special summon, but it's a tuner which means you can go into Black Rose Dragon to wipe your opponent's board going second. I also added Brionac, Dragon of The Ice Barrier to deal with annoying boss monsters like Thunder Dragon Colossus. With Brionac's effect you can send Rescue or Assault from your hand to grave which is really helpful. You can also use Destrudo to go into Brionac or Black Rose Dragon which is really helpful or if you don't have it you can summon Arboria off Isolde's second effect! There's just so many cool combos I came up with while building this deck and overall it's a really fun deck to play and most of the time will win if you go first. I really hope you guys enjoy this deck, I put a lot of time and effort playtesting it for you guys just like I do every other custom deck I post.

deck_excerpt: A Deck for fans of Red Dragon Archfiend.
deck_description:
If you know Jack and the many tuners that he uses, this deck shouldn't be that hard to use. But before using it, read the combos and more below: Combos (To get Red Dragon Archfiend on Field): Red Resonator + Red Sprinter (Red Sprinter + Red Resonator works as well. Just make sure you control no monsters when using Red Sprinter first): Summon Red Resonator, then use it's effect to Special Summon Red Sprinter. Then use both to Synchro Summon Red Rising Dragon. Use Rising Dragon's effect to bring back Red Resonator. Then Synchro Summon again to become Red Dragon Archfiend. Any Level 2 Resonator + Red Warg: This one is easy. Summon any Level 2 Resonator (Force or Red Resonator), then you should be able to Special Summon Red Warg, which should then lead to Red Dragon Archfiend. Beyond Red Dragon Archfiend: Any Level 8 "Red Dragon Archfiend" + Chain Resonator + Any Level 3 Resonator: This deck contains two Level 12 Synchros. One requires the original Red Dragon Archfiend while another doesn't. The steps are the same. With a Level 8 Red Dragon Archfiend Synchro Monster, summon Chain Resonator. Use it's effect to Special Summon a Level 3 Resonator (Clock or Dark). Then with there combined levels, tune them with a Red Dragon Archfiend to create either "Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity" or if using the original Red Dragon Archfiend, you can go for "Red Nova Dragon". Red Rising Dragon + 2 Level 2 Resonators (Red or Force): I haven't tried this one, so I don't know if it will work, but you can try. You Synchro Summon Red Rising Dragon using the above method, then instead of going to Level 8, wait until you get another Level 2 Resonator (If it's in the Graveyard, cards like "Red Carpet" and "Resonator Engine" could work). Summon the 2nd Level 2 Resonator and you should get "Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend". Red Rising Dragon + 2 Level 2 Resonators (Use 2nd Resonator after Synchro Summon with Red Rising): (Easier version of above) Summon a Level 8 red Dragon Archfiend Monster, then use the 2nd Level 2 Resonator to get "Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Bane". Any Level 8 Red Dragon Archfiend Synchro Monster + Chain Resonator (Don't need to use Chain's effect): With a Level 8 Red Dragon Archfiend Synchro, summon Chain Tinker and bring out "Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss".   NOTE:
  • If you noticed, I used one original Red Dragon Archfiend and used more of Hot. That's because the original's first effect kind of mocks me. How monsters that don't attack are destroyed isn't helpful. This may make summoning Red Nova Dragon hard. You can add two more copies of it if you want, this is just my opinion
 
  • The Continuous Trap "King Scarlet" can also be used with a Level 8 Red Dragon Archfiend Synchro Monster for "Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss"
 
  • I found "Synchro Cracker" to be very useful and fun to use. By sending a Synchro Monster you control to the Extra Deck, you can destroy all monsters your opponent controls that are weaker than the Synchro's ATK. Since a lot of cards in this deck have really high ATK power, you can use it to destroy almost all of your opponent's monsters (Like a King)
 
  • King's Synchro is also a good trap if you want to add
  That's all. Enjoy the Deck :)

  "Dark Scorpion", known as "Black Scorpion" (Kurosasori) in Japan, is an archetype of DARK Warrior monsters who have Trigger Effects that activate when they inflict battle damage to their opponent, giving the controller a choice of two effects. The majority of these card effects disrupt the opponent's field, hand or Deck, with the exception of "Dark Scorpion - Meanae the Thorn" who instead searches out other "Dark Scorpion" cards. All members of this archetype are Level 3-4 monsters, except for the Level 5 "Dark Scorpion - Gorg the Strong". The "Dark Scorpions" have been featured on numerous Spell and Trap Cards. "Don Zaloog" and "Dark Scorpion Burglars" were introduced in Pharaonic Guardian, "Cliff" in Magician's Force, and the rest in Dark Crisis.

Fusion of Fire Fusion Rise of the Salamangreat Ritual Salamangreat Circle Circle Salamangreat Claw Claw Salamangreat Gift Gift Salamangreat Rage Rage Salamangreat Recurrence Recurrence Salamangreat Roar Roar Salamangreat Sanctuary Sanctuary Will of the Salamangreat Will

Playing style

The "Salmangreat" monsters have various effects related to battle and GY recursion. A common theme among many of their monsters is they work best when with another monster of the same name. The most simple and powerful example is "Salamangreat Gazelle" who sends any "Salamangreat" card from the Deck to the GY, and can also Special Summon itself from the hand if a "Salamangreat" monster is sent to the GY. Many of the archetype's effects also involve shuffling cards from the GY into the Deck and discarding cards, so manipulation of the GY successfully gives the Deck a lot of potential. A key part of the Deck's combos is "Salamangreat Sanctuary", which allows the player to use a "Salamangreat" with the same name as a monster being Link Summoned as the entire material. As with the lesser monsters, the boss monsters get stronger when Summoned using a monster with the same name, making "Sanctuary" the quickest and easiest way to open up the full potential of the Deck's Link monsters. It can be searched by "Salamangreat Balelynx" to increase consistency. The main win condition of many builds is to set up a "Salamangreat Violet Chimera" Summoned using another copy of itself, which basically guarantees an OTK if all its effects resolve. The other Extra Deck monsters are dedicated to supporting this strategy, or for supporting the Deck's recursion/battle effects. The Deck's Ritual Monster "Salamangreat Emerald Eagle" provides a finisher/alternate attacker that can clear all the opponent's Special Summoned monsters if Ritual Summoned using an "Emerald Eagle" the player controls, and can sacrifice unneeded Link Monsters to get over tough monsters while inflicting heavy Burn damage. As any modern Deck must, the Spell/Trap lineup of the Deck also has a heavy control element. "Salamangreat Roar" is a powerful Counter Trap Card that can negate any monster effect or Spell/Trap card while you control a "Salamangreat" Link Monster, that can Set itself from the GY when a "Salamangreat" is self-Link Summoned at the cost of banishing itself when it leaves the field. It can also be recovered by "Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf", who can also play a key role in grabbing "Fusion of Fire" or other key Spell/Trap cards. Many of these get stronger when a self-Summoned Salamangreat Link Monster is present, so maintaining and protecting a powerful monster like "Salamangreat Heatleo" can reap many rewards, even over a relatively short Duel. Finally, a key step in setting up these plays is "Salamangreat Miragestallio"
